North Sea wind farms deliver 21 percent more electricity
The wind power plants on the German North Sea have fed 11.51 terawatt hours of electricity into the grid in the first six months of the year.
That is a good 21 percent more than in the same period of the previous year, the network operator Tennet said in Bayreuth.
Tennet is responsible for the transmission of the North Sea electricity to the mainland and the transmission through the German electricity grid.
The wind turbines on the Baltic Sea, which are not part of the Tennet network, have fed in an additional 2.22 terawatt hours (TWh) of electricity.
Overall, the wind power from the North and Baltic Sea comes to 13.73 TWh, compared to a good 11.64 TWh in the first half of 2019.
The wind harvest at sea accounts for almost 19 percent of the total wind power in Germany, which is about four percentage points more than a year ago.
New wind farms increase production capacities
In addition to the wind conditions, the increased contribution of offshore wind energy results from higher generation capacities, because new wind farms have been connected to the grid in the past twelve months.
If the 1,270 wind power plants in the North Sea were all running at the same time, they could generate 6.7 gigawatts of electricity.
The transmission capacity is sufficient for this; it is 7.1 gigawatts, according to Tennet.
By 2030, it is expected to rise to 17 gigawatts in the German North Sea.
“In Germany and the Netherlands, we are investing 20 billion euros in the expansion of offshore network connections by then,” said Tennet Managing Director Tim Meyerjürgens.
In reality, wind farms cannot even use their capacity at sea, but reach about 40 percent.
The previous record day this year is January 2, when the North Sea wind farms generated more than six gigawatts of electricity.
On average, the North Sea wind turbines produce about 2.5 to 3.0 gigawatts of electricity, which is equivalent to three to four nuclear power plants.
This could supply nearly seven million households with electricity.
